You can access audit logs programmatically over graphql ([example for setting up a client](https://docs.dagster.io/concepts/webserver/graphql-client#using-the-graphql-client)). Here's an example query:

```gql
query AuditLogQuery($limit: Int, $cursor: String, $filters: AuditLogFilters) {
    auditLog {
        auditLogEntries(limit: $limit, cursor: $cursor, filters: $filters) {
            id
            eventType
            authorUserEmail
            authorAgentTokenId
            eventMetadata
            timestamp
            deploymentName
        }
    }
}
```

The returned id can be used as the cursor to paginate followup queries.

Note that audit logs are only accessible by [organization admins](https://docs.dagster.io/dagster-plus/account/managing-users/managing-user-roles-permissions#workspace-administration) and only available on [Dagster+ Pro plans](https://dagster.io/enterprise).

